claims:
1. A powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument comprising:
at least one sensor to measure at least one parameter associated with an operation of the instrument;
at least one processor; and
a memory operatively associated with the processor, the memory including machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to:
monitor the at least one sensor;
prevent the instrument from continuing its current operation when the parameter measured by the at least one sensor exceeds a threshold;
continue to monitor the at least one sensor over a predetermined time period;
determine a rate of change of the measured parameter;
permit the instrument to continue performing the current operation when the measured parameter returns below the threshold.
2. The powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument of claim 1, comprising an end effector comprising a first jaw member and a second jaw member, wherein at least one of the first and second jaw members is movable relative to the other jaw member, and wherein the at least one sensor is positioned on at least one of the first and second jaw members.
3. The powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument of claim 2, further comprising:
a knife channel defined in at least one of the first or second jaw members;
a knife configured to translate along the knife channel;
a motor operatively coupled to the knife to advance and retract the knife along the knife channel; and
a current sensor configured to measure current draw of the motor while the motor advances the knife to cut tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members;
wherein the processor is configured to receive a signal from the current sensor over the predetermined time period, wherein the signal is representative of the current draw of the motor while the motor advances the knife through the tissue; and
wherein the processor is configured to determine a rate of change of the current draw of the motor while the motor advances the knife through the tissue over the predetermined time period.
4. The powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument of claim 2, further comprising a force sensor positioned in at least one of the first or second jaw members to measure compression of tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members, wherein the processor is configured to receive a signal from the force sensor over the predetermined time period, wherein the signal is representative of the tissue compression, and wherein the processor is configured to determine a rate of change of tissue compression over the predetermined time period.
5. A powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument comprising:
an end effector comprising a first jaw member and a second jaw member, wherein at least one of the first and second jaw members is movable relative to the other jaw member during a jaw closure stroke;
a pressure sensor or strain gauge positioned in at least one of the first or second jaw members;
at least one processor;
a memory operatively associated with the processor, the memory including machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to:
monitor the pressure applied to tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members during the jaw closure stroke;
cause the instrument to pause the jaw closure stroke when the applied pressure exceeds a predetermined threshold;
continue to monitor the applied pressure for a predetermined time period after the jaw closure stroke is paused;
cause the instrument to continue the jaw closure stroke when the applied pressure returns below the predetermined threshold; and
determine a type of tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members based on the tissue pressure measurement.
6. A powered surgical cutting and stapling instrument comprising:
an end effector comprising a first jaw member and a second jaw member, wherein at least one of the first and second jaw members is movable relative to the other jaw member;
a pressure sensor or strain gauge positioned in at least one of the first or second jaw members;
a gap sensor to measure a gap distance between the first and second jaw members;
at least one processor;
a memory operatively associated with the processor, the memory including machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to:
monitor the pressure applied to tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members;
monitor the gap distance between the first and second jaw members, wherein the pressure and gap distance measurements are used by the processor to determine an amount of tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members, and wherein when a small portion of the first and second jaw members are covered in tissue, the processor is configured to compensate tissue compression measurements; and
determine a type of tissue grasped between the first and second jaw members based on the tissue pressure and the gap distance measurement.
7. A powered surgical instrument, comprising:
a sensing system to measure at least one parameter associated with the instrument;
at least one processor; and
a memory operatively associated with the processor, the memory including machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to:
monitor the at least one parameter measured by the sensing system;
cause the instrument to pause a current operation when the measured parameter exceeds a threshold;
continue to monitor the measured parameter for a predetermined time period after the current operation of the instrument is paused; and
cause the instrument to continue performing the current operation when the measured parameter is below the threshold.
8. The powered surgical instrument of claim 7, wherein the memory further includes machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to prevent the instrument from performing the current operation until the measured parameter is below the threshold.
9. The powered surgical instrument of claim 7, further comprising an end effector comprising a first jaw member and a second jaw member, wherein at least one of the first and second jaw members is movable relative to the other jaw member.
10. The powered surgical instrument of claim 9, wherein the current operation of the instrument is a jaw closure operation.
11. The powered surgical instrument of claim 7, wherein the current operation of the instrument is a firing operation.
12. The powered surgical instrument of claim 7, wherein the threshold comprises a pre-defined force threshold.
13. The powered surgical instrument of claim 7, wherein the threshold comprises a pre-defined pressure threshold.
14. A motor-powered surgical instrument, comprising:
a sensing system that measures a parameter associated with the instrument;
a processor; and
a memory device operatively associated with the processor, the memory device including machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to:
monitor the parameter measured by the sensing system;
cause the instrument to pause a current operation of the instrument when the measured parameter exceeds a threshold;
continue to monitor the measured parameter for a predetermined time period after the current operation of the instrument is paused; and enable the instrument to continue performing the paused operation of the instrument when the measured parameter is below the threshold.
15. The motor-powered surgical instrument of claim 14, wherein the memory device further includes machine executable instructions that when executed by the processor cause the processor to prevent the instrument from performing the paused operation of the instrument until the measured parameter is below the threshold.
16. The motor-powered surgical instrument of claim 14, further comprising an end effector comprising a first jaw member and a second jaw member, wherein at least one of the first and second jaw members is movable relative to the other jaw member, and wherein the current operation of the instrument is a jaw closure operation.
17. The motor-powered surgical instrument of claim 14, further comprising a staple cartridge including staples removably stored therein, wherein the current operation of the instrument is a firing operation that fires the staples from the staple cartridge.
18. The motor-powered surgical instrument of claim 14, wherein the threshold comprises a pre-defined force threshold.
19. The motor-powered surgical instrument of claim 14, wherein the threshold comprises a pre-defined pressure threshold.
